#=GF CC   This is a membrane localization domain found in multiple
#=GF CC   families of bacterial toxins including all of the clostridial
#=GF CC   glucosyltransferase toxins and various MARTX toxins
#=GF CC   (multifunctional-autoprocessing RTX toxins) [1,4]. In the
#=GF CC   Pasteurella multocida toxin (PMT) C-terminal fragment,
#=GF CC   structural analysis have indicated that the C1 domain possesses
#=GF CC   a signal that leads the toxin to the cell membrane. Furthermore,
#=GF CC   the C1 domain was found to structurally resemble the
#=GF CC   phospholipid-binding domain of C. difficile toxin B [2].
#=GF CC   Functional studies in Vibrio cholera indicate that the subdomain
#=GF CC   at the N terminus of RID (Rho-inactivation domain), homologous
#=GF CC   to the membrane targeting C1 domain of Pasteurella multocida
#=GF CC   toxin, is a conserved membrane localization domain essential for
#=GF CC   proper localization [1]. The Rho-inactivation domain (RID) of
#=GF CC   MARTX (Multifunctional Autoprocessing RTX toxin) is responsible
#=GF CC   for inactivating the Rho-family of small GTPases in Vibrio
#=GF CC   cholerae. It is a bacterial toxin that self-process by a
#=GF CC   cysteine peptidase mechanism [3]. The Vibrio cholerae RTX toxin
#=GF CC   is an autoprocessing cysteine protease whose activity is
#=GF CC   stimulated by the intracellular environment [3]. This cysteine
#=GF CC   peptidase belongs to MEROPS peptidase family G6.
